Metcash launches down-to-earth campaign to combat Aldi incursion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA stores from an Aldi march in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a down-to-earth campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in the run-up to a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares the opening of two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media, as well as through events such as Adelaide show.
IGA distributors and suppliers jump on board, with brands such as ice cream maker Simmo from Dunsborough distributing samples in IGA stores and shopkeepers selling discounted tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to provide further details of its defense strategy on the 29th. September published when the wholesaler of food, alcohol and equipment conducts its annual investor strategy day.
There is a lot at stake, as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 per cent of Metcash's IGA store deals and generating higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 per cent in South Australia and 24 per cent in Western Australia compared to around 14 per cent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snatch away around five percent of the food market in these two states and take away sales from all existing players but mainly self-employed retailers.
According to a report published this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and food business and in the quantities on Metcash's high fixed cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mostly to Aldi and Coles, though a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley assumes that Metcash's food and grocery sales will fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a Melbourne business lunch that Metcash is likely within a decade. Metcash will disappear.
Metcash declined to publicly respond to Mr Douglass' comments.
But it is expected that a board member of Metcash made contact with Mr Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and income from Metcash's food and food trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operating debt reduction while putting pressure on revenue and margins.
However, the wholesaler is fighting back, investing more than $150 million to align sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week, and to improve IGA retailers in improving their stores through faster-growing fresh food and delivering a better selection of private label food.
Metcash's chief executive Ian Morrice says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will gain steam and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is backed by the president of the Australian Tennis Federation Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to the president of Australian tennis federation Steve Healy, deserves more praise than criticism for his own behaviour.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks," came into the spotlight by Kyrgios' infamous altercation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifier in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison exclaiming: "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should beat the child."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a convulsion thwarted a potential U.S. Open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the individual behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Britain.
"One thing I'm quite jealous of is the fact that, in my view, Thanasi was drawn a little into the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost because of a cramp in the U.S. Open, but he's not the first player to break a bat out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he has behaved extremely well in the U.S. Open, even under the pretty provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of credit.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I believe he has been treated a little too hard.
He's a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he's never had a problem with the other players, he's respected in the locker room, he's training hard, he's in good shape, he's a very stable and mature young guy, and I believe he deserves to be judged by his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to consider Kyrgios in the important preliminary decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the "common decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the man from Canberra to return to the team as a long-term permanent component."
"First, we wish the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I believe that Nick managed the climb very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time outside the spotlight where he can only think about it, I think is appropriate, and it's best for the squad and it's the best for him.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes border, withholds refugees
Hungary declares a state of emergency and sealed off the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, holding on to all those who tried to enter the country illegally. All with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man's land and Serbian officials responded with outrage.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations rose.
When a police helicopter floated above them, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults against Hungarian riot police.
Some rejected food and water in protest.
Serbia's foreign minister declared it was "unacceptable" that migrants would be sent back from Hungary, while more and more arriving from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution, not collateral damage.
Talks will have to take place with Brussels and other countries in the coming days," Ivica Dacic said in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serb border failed to agree on a joint immigration policy a day after the 28-nation bloc at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
However, ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in the surprised Italy and Greece. They expressed their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that EU states would take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special summit of the European Union to discuss the continent's immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not put its hopes on an action soon from Brussels or from its neighbours.
The state of emergency declared on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis so that they could block off roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto, meanwhile, said his country was also planning to build a barbed-wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were deployed in the race to create the barbed-wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a significant bottleneck for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East and a point of entry into the European Union.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most of the arriving are economic refugees who are looking for a better life, rather than war refugees who are entitled to protection - a view that is strongly at odds with other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot)-high fence, which the government built along the southern border with Serbia, a crime. These laws also set higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares a state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovac's reporters in the southern city of Szeged said.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to agree procedurally to the deployment of the military, which is expected to last next week, but Associated Press reporters have already seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, country's security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already entered the country deeper.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train carriage with barbed wire to close the borders arrived.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to edit the data of people and squeezed a crowd to crowd in there.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands stayed outside.
Another group of migrants blocked Serbia's and Hungarians' main highway link, saying they would deny food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
Election-2016: Hillary Clinton's lead over Bernie Sanders halved in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the Democratic race for the nomination nationally, but Senator Bernie Sanders is gaining ground over her.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries (58 percent before), while Sanders is second, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he will run for president, will receive support from 15 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries.
More than five months before the primaries begin, most Democratic voters say it's too early to say their opinion is determined which candidate they will support.
But Clinton's supporters are more consistent in her election than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS news poll, Clinton has lost on a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some gains.
Clinton holds a big lead in women and moderates, but those protrusions have diminished.
Their support among the men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind here.
Clinton's advantage among Democratic voters under the age of 50 has evaporated, and she and Sanders are now at the same height.
Clinton, however, still has a big lead among senior voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a double-digit lead among the Liberals, but Sanders now has a 5-point lead in this group.
About half of Democratic voters in the primaries nationwide say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some caveats and another 15 percent would only support her because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support them.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton's current supporters are mostly excited about her.
The views are more mixed with those who currently don't support Clinton - only about a quarter would enthusiastically support them.
While 48 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries say they support Clinton with enthusiasm, fewer Republican voters say so about their front-runner Donald Trump (35 percent).
If Clinton's supporters are asked on an open-ended question about why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it's time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she is the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton's supporters also mention her association with Bill Clinton (9 percent).
Approval of dealing with the problems and electability are also cited.
With the vice president throwing a potential for presidential office into the balance, 57 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries would like to see him in the race - though a third believe he shouldn't.
When Democratic voters of the primaries are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
Of Clinton's supporters, more than half say Biden would be her second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton's lead over Sanders, from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race, is up.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as a candidate with the best chance of winning the election; however, that figure has dropped from 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second in that measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the "most electable" has risen.
Still, when asked what's more important to a candidate, Democratic voters are citing questions about electability.
Similar to last month, not a single Democratic candidate or potential candidate stands out as unacceptable to these voters of the primaries.
The Democratic candidates or potential candidates produce good results on some key features among voters in their party's primary.
Majorities consider Clinton, Sanders and Biden to be honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership skills.
Biden scores best on honesty on the three candidates, while Clinton's strength is the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don't believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent have no opinion on it.
Democratic voters of the primaries generally also see Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in accordance with their views.
With all these measurements, about a quarter of Democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
Since questions about Hillary Clinton's use of a personal email address and a server during the tenure as secretary of state continue to be asked, most Democratic voters of the primaries are satisfied with their explanation of the matter, saying it has not affected their opinions overall.
But it's a different story in the American public overall.
Half of Americans are now unhappy with their explanation, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no effect on her general opinions from Clinton, though 36 percent said her opinion of her had still deteriorated.
It's mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10 who say their views have gotten worse from Clinton.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party's voters, this continues to be a problem for her among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see her as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month and 15 points less since May.
62 percent of eligible voters do not consider them an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of eligible voters nationwide also see Trump as not honest and untrustworthy.
Clinton and Trump, however, receive good marks on leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush score best on honesty.
