Five members of the Brotherhood charged with the death of a Baruch college freshman
Nearly two years after a student passed away during a bullying ritual of a student association in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of New York's Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transport to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he had been blindfolded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand, and repeatedly attacked while trying to walk across a frozen field to a target.
Mr. Deng eventually complained of headaches, then fell unconscious.
Members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call emergency number 911 after Deng passed out and reportedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, according to police.
However, they had the time to change Deng's clothes, Google his symptoms and contact Andy Meng, the national president of the Brotherhood, to seek advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a news conference.
"At this point, members began to hide utensils and basically put the welfare of the Brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," police chief Wagner said.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
After an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly inflicted with dull force injuries to the head, trunk and thigh.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the harassment of the Brotherhood. At least one student has died of harassment every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this move by authorities is very important.
A County Grand Jury of Monroe recommended a charge of third-degree murder for the first five members.
Thirty-two Brotherhood members, including Mr Meng, are also charged with bullying attacks and forming a criminal association.
"We not only want to hold the people involved responsible, but if there is an organization that has - officially or unofficially - sanctioned this, so we will also hold these to account," Wagner said at a news conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its affiliation with the local group.
That will happen when the Fed raises interest rates
A rate hike is coming, and the house is simmering, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long this will all last and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance to the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, though not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. Central Bank have so fiercely emphasized that investors should not focus on when it begins to raise interest rates, but rather to the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants could find that all the excitement may have been exaggerated because of a rate hike.
"The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal to the end of the era of "cheap money,"" Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to clients.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still at too low a level to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, that does not mean there will be no impact.
Here’s a look based on historical trends at how some areas of the economy might respond:
As the market has seen last month, anticipating interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase arrives, the influence is not so dramatic.
"There is apparently a tendency for asset income to be choked off 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which perhaps again reflects the delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after interest rate hikes by the Fed.
More specifically, the market is mostly on the uptrend in the past 35 years - about 14 percent - on the way to raising interest rates, quite flat in the 250 days after that (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the past six past cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, at Barron's
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the stocks tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the yield is starting to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate hikes often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed faces some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely remarkable that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point in a Fed interest rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate hikes since 1950 have only twice been nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was at 3.6 percent, few expect this to last and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes on such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raise the question of "whether it's different this time," Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been prepared for a Fed rate hike throughout the year, and all eyes were on the meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
"In our study, all increase cycles from 1950 to the present have taken place in a supercycle with increasing momentum in GDP and dwarfed pre-recession heights very quickly after the start of the recovery," the report said.
By contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile, as the market anticipates an interest rate hike, and the pattern is quite similar to that on the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than with equities, if they change their strategic course.
For bonds, yields appear to be changing direction once the first increase/lowering occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab's strategists believe the rise in interest rates will cause yields to move closer together between longer and shorter bonds and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-income bonds often yield better yields in such a climate, though "we are still cautious about expecting higher yields," Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
What is interesting, Jones thinks, is that the markets have already adjusted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the dollar's strength and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of stricter monetary policy," she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have widened and volatility has risen - all features of the market if the Fed tightens its strategy.
By and large, companies that handle the greater share of their business in the U.S. will benefit when interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debts will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and also the financing of their debts.
"History shows that "quality" stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Companies with a strong balance sheet exceeded companies with a weak balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate hikes in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debts are going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits through higher yields, even if experts disagree on how fast that will take place.
