Robotic cars: Government wants pioneering role for Germany
According to the will of the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the change of the car.
The Federal Cabinet on Wednesday approved a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the IAA car fair of a "new mobility age."
Automated and connected driving will increase road safety and cause less traffic jams, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid switch to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being built on Autobahn 9 in Bavaria.
In order to "not impose any additional liability risks" on the driver, the federal government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to the new developments."
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the permissible maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometers per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to campaign for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for the people as drivers.
When driving automatically, the car increasingly takes the lead, the driver becomes more and more a passenger.
The technology is primarily based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study submitted by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are "only to be expected well after 2020."
The authors of the study estimate the added value in the field of driver assistance systems and the highly automated driving functions at the location in Germany at around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said the SPD transport politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the safety of the personal data of the drivers must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still see self-driving cars as skeptical - much more than French or American.
A survey conducted on Wednesday at the AA by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the testing organization Dekra concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomously driving cars will prevail in the next decade, 32 percent do not expect it until 20 years, 31 percent do not believe in it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, and 33 percent in the US.
In any case, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to hand over control throughout the entire ride on all roads.
On the highway, this could be imagined in flowing traffic at least 15 percent, in traffic jams 45 percent.
Well one in four would leave control to the car under no circumstances.
