EU to double mercury limit in predator fish
The European Commission wants to double the limits for mercury in large predator fish and thus expect consumers to have a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticised the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on with full force to pregnant women and young children," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve agent for large fish at the end of the food chain such as shark or swordfish are to be raised for "economic policy reasons" from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish.
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold on the basis of the limit values still in force.
After the doubling of the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsaleable.
In return for this easing, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limits on other fish from the current 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
However, Foodwatch described this as a "trick" because smaller peace fish, such as carp, are usually so low-stressed that they already meet the planned highs today.
The lowering of small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction that alone helps the economy," explained Wolfschmidt.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which is greatly enriched via the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn babies."
However, the Federal Environment Ministry declares on its homepage with regard to the applicable maximum values, however, that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through coal combustion.
According to written information from the Federal Environment Ministry, the German coal-fired power plants eject the Greens’ member of the Bundestag, Annalena Baerbock, more than six tonnes of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount issued in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and nationwide exceeded," the "Spiegel" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings about mercury in fish were already among the most common reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
